<paragraph blockId="12.[163,779,1317,1707]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">
<emphasis box="[163,369,1317,1338]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">Male description:</emphasis>
Measurements (
<specimenCount box="[584,778,1317,1339]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436" type="generic">three specimens</specimenCount>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[235,312,1348,1370]" country="Italy" name="Sicilia" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">Sicily</collectingRegion>
): CL = 875–1093; CW = 781–1000; SL = 937–1001; ML = 2281–2437; MW = 1062–1218; EW = 300–387; EL = 462–525; CS = 828–1046; CL/ CW = 1.09–1.17; SL/CS = 0.92–1.20; ML/CS = 2.32– 2.75. Small, subrectangular head with large ocelli and large eyes protruding laterally. Toothless mandibles. Relatively large mesosoma, propodeum more gently rounded than in queens or workers. Low, round petiolar node. Weak sculpture, shiny mesosoma. Hairy mandibles, other hairs on clypeus and gaster. Entire body ferruginous or brownish, gaster blackish. See 
<figureCitation box="[163,272,1685,1707]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="17.[145,226,1268,1290]" captionTargetBox="[145,1374,195,1228]" captionTargetId="figure-302@17.[145,1425,195,1228]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figure 11. Colobopsis imitans. A, B, E, F, queen; C, D, G, male. Specimens from the type locality. Scale bars: 0.5 mm. Pictures also available on AntWeb.org database, specimen codes: ANTWEB1041483 and ANTWEB1041484." pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">
Figure 
<figureCitation box="[245,272,1686,1707]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="17.[145,226,1268,1290]" captionTargetBox="[145,1374,195,1228]" captionTargetId="figure-302@17.[145,1425,195,1228]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figure 11. Colobopsis imitans. A, B, E, F, queen; C, D, G, male. Specimens from the type locality. Scale bars: 0.5 mm. Pictures also available on AntWeb.org database, specimen codes: ANTWEB1041483 and ANTWEB1041484." pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">11</figureCitation>
</figureCitation>
. Genitalia as in 
<figureCitation box="[461,570,1685,1707]" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="18.[163,245,788,810]" captionTargetBox="[163,1443,195,748]" captionTargetId="figure-591@18.[163,1443,195,748]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figure 12. Male genitalia of Colobopsis imitans in ventral and dorsal view, specimen from the type locality. Scale bars = 0.25 mm." pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">
Figure 
<figureCitation box="[543,570,1686,1707]" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="18.[163,245,788,810]" captionTargetBox="[163,1443,195,748]" captionTargetId="figure-591@18.[163,1443,195,748]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figure 12. Male genitalia of Colobopsis imitans in ventral and dorsal view, specimen from the type locality. Scale bars = 0.25 mm." pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">12</figureCitation>
</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[163,779,1753,1898]" lastBlockId="12.[827,1444,1132,1645]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">
<emphasis box="[163,282,1754,1775]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Generally easy to determine on the basis of worker material due to strong chromatic differentiation from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Emery &amp; Forel" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[222,360,1815,1836]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Colobopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncata">
<emphasis box="[222,360,1815,1836]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">Co. truncata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and allopatric distribution (although further investigation is required for possible contact regions in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[398,468,1876,1898]" name="Georgia" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">Iberia</collectingCountry>
and southern 
<collectingCountry box="[638,696,1876,1898]" name="Italy" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">Italy</collectingCountry>
). Some small worker specimens may appear almost completely black, therefore lacking the typical chromatic pattern; workers with entirely red mesosoma seldom observed. Tentative identifications of isolated soldier or queen specimens should be much more cautious, although their chromatic appearance may sometimes appear to be explicit. The low number of males and the lack of particularly evident distinctive characters from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Emery &amp; Forel" baseAuthorityYear="1879" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Colobopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">Co. truncata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
do not allow a safe species-level identification of this caste based on morphology. As for workers, the morphometric linear discriminant function provided in the Results section should help with dubious cases, including decoloured specimens. Finally, DNA barcoding, which can be used for the same purpose and can also be employed on the other castes, shows relatively low error rate but may present risks due to the polyphyletic pattern that we observed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[827,1443,1692,1898]" lastBlockId="13.[809,1426,787,932]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="1437" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">Biological, ecological and phenological notes:</emphasis>
Relatively thermophilous; occurring in Sicily from a few meters above sea level to at least 
<quantity box="[1357,1443,1753,1775]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.015" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436" unit="m" value="1015.0">1015 m</quantity>
elevation, ascending up to 
<quantity box="[1148,1236,1784,1805]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.29" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436" unit="m" value="1290.0">1290 m</quantity>
a.s.l. in 
<collectingCountry box="[1340,1438,1784,1805]" name="Morocco" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">Morocco</collectingCountry>
, and so far known from coastal lowland areas in 
<collectingCountry box="[1370,1439,1815,1837]" name="Spain" pageId="12" pageNumber="1436">Spain</collectingCountry>
. Probably common but also heavily under-recorded due to its cryptic arboreal lifestyle, low colony population (most-likely monogynous), effective mimicry and long periods of inactivity during the most arid and coldest times of the year. Workers and soldiers are unlikely to descend to the ground but were observed to do so at least once, following a sparsely populated 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1792" box="[608,760,910,932]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Crematogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutellaris">
<emphasis box="[608,760,910,932]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Cr. scutellaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
trail. Soldiers, in general, are difficult to find outside the nest and are usually seen acting as gatekeepers of the nest entrance. Founding queens were observed to do the same. Nests are hidden in minute holes on the dead parts of arboreal trunks, where 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schifani &amp; Giannetti &amp; Csősz &amp; Castellucci &amp; Luchetti &amp; Castracani &amp; Spotti &amp; Mori &amp; Grasso" authorityYear="2022" box="[568,696,1064,1085]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Colobopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imitans">
<emphasis box="[568,696,1064,1085]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Co. imitans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
often seems to act as secondary user of cavities excavated by xylophagous insects. It exploits 
<taxonomicName authority="(Bosc, 1792)" baseAuthorityName="Bosc" baseAuthorityYear="1792" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Andricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quercustozae">
<emphasis box="[505,761,1125,1147]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Andricus quercustozae</emphasis>
(Bosc, 1792)
</taxonomicName>
oak galls as nests [occupying about 15% of galls collected in Bosco della Ficuzza (Sicily) in a recent survey, authors’ unpublished data], in a similar way to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Emery &amp; Forel" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[145,286,1248,1269]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Colobopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncata">
<emphasis box="[145,286,1248,1269]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Co. truncata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see: 
<bibRefCitation author="Giannetti D &amp; Castracani C &amp; Spotti FA &amp; Mori A &amp; Grasso DA" box="[352,596,1248,1270]" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" pagination="392" refId="ref16484" refString="Giannetti D, Castracani C, Spotti FA, Mori A, Grasso DA. 2019. Gall-colonizing ants and their role as plant defenders: from ' bad job' to ' useful service'. Insects 10: 392." type="journal article" year="2019">
Giannetti 
<emphasis box="[470,520,1248,1269]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">et al</emphasis>
., 2019
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Giannetti D &amp; Mandrioli M &amp; Schifani E &amp; Castracani C &amp; Spotti F &amp; Mori A &amp; Grasso DA" box="[609,664,1248,1269]" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" pagination="108" refId="ref16524" refString="Giannetti D, Mandrioli M, Schifani E, Castracani C, Spotti F, Mori A, Grasso DA. 2021. First report of the acrobat ant Crematogaster scutellaris storing live aphids inside its oak-gall nests. Insects 12: 108." type="journal article" year="2021">2021</bibRefCitation>
; Fürjes- Mikó 
<emphasis box="[211,269,1278,1300]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">et al.</emphasis>
, 2020). Polydomy appears probable due to repeated findings of groups of workers with no queen within oak-galls. Nesting observed on several diverse plant species, including at least: 
<taxonomicName authority="Blanco" authorityName="Blanco" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" genus="Citrus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reticulata">
<emphasis box="[556,760,1370,1392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Citrus reticulata</emphasis>
Blanco
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[242,381,1401,1423]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" genus="Citrus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sinensis">
<emphasis box="[242,381,1401,1423]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Ci. sinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) Osbeck, 
<taxonomicName box="[544,720,1401,1423]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Laurus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis box="[544,720,1401,1423]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Laurus nobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., 
<taxonomicName box="[145,308,1432,1453]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Oleaceae" genus="Olea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="europaea">
<emphasis box="[145,308,1432,1453]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Olea europaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., 
<taxonomicName box="[352,492,1432,1453]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ilex">
<emphasis box="[352,492,1432,1453]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Quercus ilex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., 
<taxonomicName box="[536,681,1432,1453]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pubescens">
<emphasis box="[536,681,1432,1453]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Q. pubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group, 
<taxonomicName box="[145,248,1462,1484]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="suber">
<emphasis box="[145,248,1462,1484]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Q. suber</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., 
<taxonomicName box="[302,508,1463,1484]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Pyrus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="communis">
<emphasis box="[302,508,1463,1484]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Pyrus communis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Thunb.) W. T. Aiton. Dense" authorityName="W. T. Aiton. Dense" baseAuthorityName="Thunb." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Pittosporaceae" genus="Pittosporum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tobira">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Pittosporum tobira</emphasis>
(Thunb.) W.T.Aiton. Dense
</taxonomicName>
populations appear to have been found in old 
<taxonomicName box="[451,525,1524,1545]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" genus="Citrus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[451,525,1524,1545]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Citrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
orchards, relatively sparse cork oak (
<taxonomicName box="[335,428,1554,1576]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="suber">
<emphasis box="[335,428,1554,1576]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Q. suber</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) woods and also in deciduous oak forests. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schifani &amp; Giannetti &amp; Csősz &amp; Castellucci &amp; Luchetti &amp; Castracani &amp; Spotti &amp; Mori &amp; Grasso" authorityYear="2022" box="[409,545,1585,1607]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Colobopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imitans">
<emphasis box="[409,545,1585,1607]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Co. imitans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in a broad range of habitats, from cities to agricultural lands to natural forest habitats, but information available has so far been insufficient to depict a satisfactory picture of habitat preferences. Despite the earlier claim by 
<bibRefCitation author="Carpintero S &amp; Reyes-Lopez J &amp; De Reyna LA" box="[145,410,1738,1760]" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" pagination="151 - 163" refId="ref14775" refString="Carpintero S, Reyes-Lopez J, De Reyna LA. 2005. Impact of Argentine ants (Linepithema humile) on an arboreal ant community in Donana National Park, Spain. Biodiversity &amp; Conservation 14: 151 - 163." type="journal article" year="2005">
Carpintero 
<emphasis box="[276,332,1738,1760]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">et al.</emphasis>
(2005)
</bibRefCitation>
, there is currently no evidence backing the fascinating hypothesis that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schifani &amp; Giannetti &amp; Csősz &amp; Castellucci &amp; Luchetti &amp; Castracani &amp; Spotti &amp; Mori &amp; Grasso" authorityYear="2022" box="[636,761,1769,1791]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Colobopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imitans">
<emphasis box="[636,761,1769,1791]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">C. imitans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
foundress queens prefer trees hosting 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1792" box="[598,760,1800,1821]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Crematogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutellaris">
<emphasis box="[598,760,1800,1821]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Cr. scutellaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to found their colonies. A focused investigation on this topic would be interesting. Nuptial flights for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schifani &amp; Giannetti &amp; Csősz &amp; Castellucci &amp; Luchetti &amp; Castracani &amp; Spotti &amp; Mori &amp; Grasso" authorityYear="2022" box="[725,900,788,1882]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Colobopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imitans">
<emphasis box="[725,900,788,1882]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Co. imitans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occur approximately in the same period as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Emery &amp; Forel" baseAuthorityYear="1879" box="[809,948,819,840]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Colobopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncata">
<emphasis box="[809,948,819,840]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">Co. truncata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(alates in Sicily observed from June 30 to July 13, 
<emphasis box="[909,929,850,871]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1437">N</emphasis>
= 5, see Supporting Information, File S1). Winged queens and males were repeatedly seen to be attracted by artificial light at night.
</paragraph>
